Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C.

Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Zest the @lime{½}, then cut into wedges. Trim the @pak choi{1}, then thinly slice widthways.

Halve any larger @broccoli florets{200}. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}.

Trim the @aubergine{1} and slice into 1cm thick rounds, then pop onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then sprinkle over the @ground coriander{1}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

Once your oven is hot, roast the aubergine on the top shelf until soft and golden, ~{15-20%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pop the broccoli florets onto another large baking tray. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} then toss to coat. Roast on the middle shelf until crispy and slightly charred, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pop a medium #saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting #lid{}) on medium-high heat with a knob of @butter{knob} (if you have any - or just use a drizzle of @oil{}).

When hot, add the shallot and cook until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Add half the garlic and stir-fry for ~{1%minute}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150}, @vegetable stock paste{10} and the cold @water{300} for the rice and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave the rice to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until you're ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the pak choi and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir-fry until tender, ~{3-4%minutes}, then add the remaining garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Once cooked, transfer to a #bowl{} and cover to keep warm.

Pop your (now empty) frying pan back on medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. Add the @yellow Thai style paste{1} and stir-fry until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in the @coconut milk{200}, @peanut butter{1} and @sugar{¼%tsp} and bring to the boil. Simmer until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove from the heat. Squeeze in some lime juice and season to taste.

Just before everything is ready, reheat the sauce if necessary.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}, then stir through the pak choi and lime zest. Spoon into your bowls and top with the roasted aubergine and broccoli.

Spoon over the satay sauce.

> TIP: Add a splash of water if it's a little thick. Serve with the lime wedges for squeezing over. Enjoy!